revision.text:
'''Bologna School''' is a term for the group of [[composer]]s active in [[Bologna]] in the mid-late 17th century; most were associated with the [[San Petronio Basilica|church of Saint Petronius]] or the [[Accademia Filarmonica di Bologna|Accademia Filarmonica]]. They include [[Cazzati]], [[Perti]], [[G. B. Vitali]], [[Torelli]] and [[Arcangelo Corelli|Corelli]] (who had Bolognese links although he mainly worked in [[Rome]]); the school is associated with [[sacred music]] and particularly with the rise of the instrumental [[concerto]] and [[sonata]], including music for [[trumpet]] and [[String instrument|strings]], a Bolognese speciality.<ref>Oxford Grove Music Encyclopedia{{Full|date=March 2014}}<!--Presumably this refers to Grove Online, but which of its thousands of articles by thousands of authors? It has no article titled "Bologna School", and the article "Trumpet" does not confirm that trumpet-and-strings music was a Bolognese specialty.--></ref>
