{{DEFAULTSORT:Landon, Laurene}} [[Category:1957 births]] [[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]] [[Category:Actresses from Toronto]] [[Category:American entertainers]] [[Category:American film actresses]] [[Category:American people of Irish descent]] [[Category:American people of Polish descent]] [[Category:American television actresses]] [[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]] [[Category:Living people]]

{{Hindu scriptures|image=1_dancing_Hindu_god_Shiva_Nataraja_Tanjore,_India.jpg}}
The '''''Nāṭya Śāstra''''' ([[Sanskrit]]: नाट्य शास्त्र, ''Nāṭyaśāstra'') is a Sanskrit text on the [[performing arts]].<ref name=katherineyoung20>{{cite book|author1=Katherine Young |author2=Arvind Sharma |title=Her Voice, Her Faith: Women Speak on World Religions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xUoEw0IQvPEC |year=2004|publisher=Westview Press |isbn=978-0-8133-4666-3 |pages=20–21 }}</ref><ref name="GuyBeckp138">{{cite book|author=Guy L. Beck|title=Sonic Liturgy: Ritual and Music in Hindu Tradition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UzUMCAAAQBAJ |year=2012|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|isbn=978-1-61117-108-2|pages=138–139 |quote='''Quote:''' "A summation of the signal importance of the Natyasastra for Hindu religion and culture has been provided by Susan Schwartz, "In short, the Natyasastra is an exhaustive encyclopedic dissertation of the arts, with an emphasis on performing arts as its central feature. It is also full of invocations to deities, acknowledging the divine origins of the arts and the central role of performance arts in achieving divine goals (...)".}}</ref> The text is attributed to sage [[Bharata Muni]], and its first complete compilation is dated to between 200&nbsp;BCE and 200&nbsp;CE,{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|pp=xxiv, 19–20}} but estimates vary between 500&nbsp;BCE and 500&nbsp;CE.{{Sfn|Wallace Dace|1963|p=249}}

The text consists of 36 chapters with a cumulative total of 6000 poetic verses describing performance arts. The subjects covered by the treatise include dramatic composition, structure of a play and the construction of a stage to host it, genres of acting, body movements, make up and costumes, role and goals of an art director, the musical scales, musical instruments and the integration of music with art performance.{{Sfn|Sreenath Nair|2015}}{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|pp=3–4, 7–25}}
[[File:Natya Shastra.png|thumb]]
The ''Nāṭya Śāstra'' is notable as an ancient encyclopedic treatise on the arts,<ref name="GuyBeckp138"/><ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/> one which has influenced dance, music and literary traditions in India.{{Sfn|Sunil Kothari|Avinash Pasricha|2001|p=117, 163}} It is also notable for its aesthetic [[Rasa (aesthetics)|"Rasa"]] theory, which asserts that entertainment is a desired effect of performance arts but not the primary goal, and that the primary goal is to transport the individual in the audience into another parallel reality, full of wonder, where he experiences the essence of his own consciousness, and reflects on spiritual and moral questions.<ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/><ref>{{cite book|author=Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe |title=Approaches to Acting: Past and Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-KiJn_o4R5MC |year=2005|publisher= Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-4411-0381-9|pages=102–104, 155–156}}</ref> The text has inspired secondary literature such as Sanskrit [[bhasya]] (reviews and commentaries) such as by the 10th century [[Abhinavagupta]].{{Sfn|Ananda Lal|2004|p=308}}

==Etymology==
The title of the text is composed of two words, "Nāṭya" and "Śāstra". The root of the [[Sanskrit]] word ''Natya'' is ''Nat'' (नाट) which means "act, represent".<ref>{{cite book|author=Chandra Rajan|title=Loom Of Time, Kalidasa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sj9hZYZrcFEC |year=1999|publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=978-0-14-400078-4 |pages=29 }}</ref> The word ''Shastra'' (शास्त्र) means "precept, rules, manual, compendium, book or treatise", and is generally used as a suffix in the [[India]]n literature context, for knowledge in a defined area of practice.<ref name=lochtefeldshastra626>James Lochtefeld (2002), "Shastra" in The Illustrated Encyclopedia of Hinduism, Vol. 2: N-Z, Rosen Publishing, {{ISBN|0-8239-2287-1}}, page 626; See also [http://www.sanskrit-lexicon.uni-koeln.de/scans/MWScan/2014/web/webtc/indexcaller.php?input=HK&output=SktRomanUnicode&citation=zAstra शास्त्र] in Monier William's Sanskrit-English Dictionary, 2nd Edition, Oxford University Press, Archived by Koeln University, Germany</ref>

==Date and author==
{{Quote box | bgcolor=#FFE0BB |align=right 
|quote= '''Performance arts and culture'''
<poem>
Let Nātya (drama and dance) be the fifth [[Vedas|vedic scripture]].
Combined with an epic story, 
tending to virtue, wealth, joy and spiritual freedom, 
it must contain the significance of every scripture, 
and forward every art.
</poem>
|source =— ''Nātyaśāstra'' 1.14–15<ref>{{Cite web|title=Natyashastra|publisher = Sanskrit Documents| url=http://sanskritdocuments.org/all_pdf/natya01.pdf}}</ref><ref name=mog17>{{cite web|title=The Mirror of Gesture|author=Coormaraswamy and Duggirala|publisher=Harvard University Press|year=1917|page=4|url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924012568535#page/n5/mode/2up}}; Also see chapter 36</ref>}}
The composition date of ''Natyashastra'' is unknown, estimates vary between 500 BCE to 500 CE.{{Sfn|Wallace Dace|1963|p=249}}{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}} The text may have started in the 1st millennium BCE,{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|pp=xxiv, 19–20}} expanded over time, and most scholars suggest, based on mention of this text in other Indian literature, that the first complete version of the text was likely finished between 200 BCE to 200 CE.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn|Sreenath Nair|2015}} The ''Natya Shastra'' is traditionally alleged to be linked to a 36,000 verse Vedic composition called ''Adibharata'', however there is no corroborating evidence that such a text ever existed.<ref>{{cite book |last = Ghosh |first = Manomohan |title = Natyasastra |year = 2002 |isbn =81-7080-076-5|page =2 note 7–12|url= https://archive.org/stream/NatyaShastra/natya_shastra_translation_volume_1_-_bharat_muni#page/n87/mode/2up }}</ref>

The text has survived into the modern age in several manuscript versions, wherein the title of the chapters vary and in some cases the content of the few chapters differ.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}} Some recensions show significant interpolations and corruption of the text,{{Sfn|Nina Mirnig|Peter-Daniel Szanto|Michael Williams|2013|p=350}} along with internal contradictions and sudden changes in style.<ref>{{cite book|author=Kale Pramod |title=The Theatric Universe: (a Study of the Natyasastra) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRdNBKIHnjkC |date=1974 |publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-118-8 |pages=10–11}}</ref> Scholars such as PV Kane state that some text was likely changed as well as added to the original between the 3rd to 8th century CE, thus creating some variant editions, and the mixture of poetic verses and prose in a few extant manuscripts of ''Natyasastra'' may be because of this.<ref name=kpramodp8/>{{Sfn|Pandurang Vaman Kane|1971|pp=11–15}} According to Pramod Kale, who received a doctorate on the text from the University of Wisconsin, the surviving version of ''Natya Shastra'' likely existed by the 8th-century.<ref name=kpramodp8/>

The author of the ''Natya Shastra'' is unknown, and the Hindu tradition attributes it to the ''[[Rishi]]'' (sage) [[Bharata Muni|Bharata]]. It may be the work of several authors, but scholars disagree.<ref name=kpramodp8>{{cite book|author=Kale Pramod |title=The Theatric Universe: (a Study of the Natyasastra) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRdNBKIHnjkC |date=1974 |publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-118-8 |pages=8–9 }}</ref>{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|pp=9–10}} Bharat Gupt states that the text stylistically shows characteristics of a single compiler in the existing version, a view shared by [[Kapila Vatsyayan]].{{Sfn| Kapila Vatsyayan | 2001|p=6}}<ref name=ghosh>{{cite book|author = Manmohan Ghosh, ed. |title= Natyashastra,|publisher = [[Asiatic Society]], |location= Calcutta|year = 1950}} See introduction p. xxvi for discussion of dates</ref> The ''[[Agni Purana]]'', a generic encyclopedia, includes chapters on dramatic arts and poetry, which follow the ''Natyashastra'' format, but enumerates more styles and types of performance arts, which states Winternitz, may reflect an expansion in studies of the arts by the time ''Agni Purana'' was composed.{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|p=11}}

===Historical roots===
The ''Natyashastra'' is the oldest surviving ancient Indian work on performance arts.<ref name="Schwartz2004p12">{{cite book|author=Susan L. Schwartz |title=Rasa: Performing the Divine in India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-BXVSmT1WhMC |year=2004|publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=978-0-231-13144-5|pages=12–15}}</ref> The roots of the text extend at least as far back as the ''Natasutras'', dated to around the mid 1st millennium BCE.{{Sfn|Ananda Lal|2004|p=16}}<ref name="Lidova1994p111">{{cite book|author=Natalia Lidova |title=Drama and Ritual of Early Hinduism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3TKarwqJJP0C |date=1994 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1234-5 |pages=111–113}}</ref> 

The ''Natasutras'' are mentioned in the text of [[Pāṇini|Panini]], the sage who wrote the classic on [[Vyakarana|Sanskrit grammar]], and who is dated to about 500 BCE.<ref name="Lidova1994p111"/>{{Sfn|Farley P. Richmond|Darius L. Swann|Phillip B. Zarrilli|1993|p=30}} This performance arts related [[Sutra]] text is mentioned in other late Vedic texts, as are two scholars names Shilalin ([[IAST]]: Śilālin) and Krishashva (Kṛśaśva), credited to be pioneers in the studies of ancient drama, singing, dance and Sanskrit compositions for these arts.<ref name="Lidova1994p111"/>{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|pp=xxiv, xxxi–xxxii, 17}} The ''Natyashastra'' refers to drama performers as Śhailālinas, likely because they were so known at the time the text was written, a name derived from the legacy of the vedic sage Śilālin credited with ''Natasutras''.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|1994|p=112}} Richmond et al. estimate the ''Natasutras'' to have been composed around 600 BCE.{{Sfn|Farley P. Richmond|Darius L. Swann|Phillip B. Zarrilli|1993|p=30}}

According to Lewis Rowell, a professor of Music specializing on classical Indian music, the earliest Indian artistic thought included three arts, syllabic recital (''vadya''), melos (''gita'') and dance (''nrtta''),{{Sfn|Rowell|2015|p=9}} as well as two musical genre, ''Gandharva'' (formal, composed, ceremonial music) and ''Gana'' (informal, improvised, entertainment music).{{Sfn|Rowell|2015|pp=11-12}} The ''Gandharva'' subgenre also implied celestial, divine associations, while the ''Gana'' was free form art and included singing.{{Sfn|Rowell|2015|pp=11-12}} The Sanskrit musical tradition spread widely in the Indian subcontinent during the late 1st millennium BCE, and the ancient Tamil classics make it “abundantly clear that a cultivated musical tradition existed in South India as early as the last few pre-Christian centuries”.{{Sfn|Rowell|2015|pp=12-13}}

The art schools of Shilalin and Krishashva, mentioned in both the [[Brahmana]]s and the [[Kalpa (Vedanga)|Kalpasutras and Srautasutras]],<ref name="Lidova1994p112">{{cite book|author=Natalia Lidova |title=Drama and Ritual of Early Hinduism |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3TKarwqJJP0C |date=1994 |publisher=Motilal Banarsidass |isbn=978-81-208-1234-5 |pages=112}}</ref> may have been associated with the performance of vedic rituals, which involved storytelling with embedded ethical values.<ref name="Lidova1994p112"/> The [[Vedanga]] texts such as verse 1.4.29 of ''Panini Sutras'' mention these as well. The roots of the ''Natyashastra'' thus likely trace to the more ancient vedic traditions of integrating ritual recitation, dialogue and song in a dramatic representation of spiritual themes.<ref name=varadpande45/>{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|pp=181–182}} The Sanskrit verses in chapter 13.2 of [[Shatapatha Brahmana]] (~800–700 BCE), for example, are written in the form of a riddle play between two actors.<ref>ML Varadpande (1990), History of Indian Theatre, Volume 1, Abhinav, {{ISBN|978-8170172789}}, page 48</ref>

{{Quote|
The Vedic sacrifice (''[[yajna]]'') is presented as a kind of drama, with its actors, its dialogues, its portion to be set to music, its interludes, and its climaxes.
|[[Louis Renou]]|Vedic India<ref name=varadpande45>ML Varadpande (1990), History of Indian Theatre, Volume 1, Abhinav, {{ISBN|978-8170172789}}, pages 45–47</ref>}}

==Features==
[[File:Sitara Thobani Odissi classical dance mudra India (16).jpg|thumb|170px|The Natyasastra discusses dance and many other performance arts.]]
The most studied version of the text, consisting of about 6000 poetic verses, is structured into 36 chapters.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}} The tradition believes that the text originally had 12,000 verses.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|pp=1–25}} Somewhat different versions of the manuscripts exist, and these contain 37 or 38 chapters.{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|p=7}}{{Sfn|Pandurang Vaman Kane|1971|p=11}} Predominant number of its verses are in precise [[Sanskrit prosody|Anustubh meter]] (4x8, or exactly 32 syllables in every ''shloka''), some verses are in Arya meter (a morae-based Sanskrit meter), and the text has some text that is in prose particularly in chapters 6, 7 and 28.{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|p=7}}{{Sfn|Pandurang Vaman Kane|1971|pp=15–16}}

The structure of the text harmoniously compiles aspects of the theatrical arts into separate chapters.{{Sfn| Kapila Vatsyayan | 2001}} The text opens with the mythical genesis and history of drama, mentions the role of different Hindu deities in various aspects of the arts, and the recommended [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]] (consecration ceremony) of a stage for performance arts.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn|Sreenath Nair|2015}}<ref name="GuyBeckp138"/> The text, states Natalia Lidova, then describes the theory of Tāṇḍava dance ([[Shiva]]), the theory of [[Rasa (aesthetics)|rasa]], of bhāva, expression, gestures, acting techniques, basic steps, standing postures.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn| Kapila Vatsyayan | 2001}}{{Sfn|Radhavallabh Tripathi|1991|pp=14–31}}

Chapters 6 and 7 present the [[Rasa (aesthetics)|"Rasa"]] theory on aesthetics in performance arts, while chapters 8 to 13 are dedicated to the art of acting.{{Sfn|Tieken|1998|p=171}}{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|p=8-9}} Stage instruments such as methods for holding accessories, weapons, relative movement of actors and actresses, scene formulation, stage zones, conventions and customs are included in chapters 10 to 13 of the ''Natyashastra''.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn|Sreenath Nair|2015}}{{Sfn|Radhavallabh Tripathi|1991|pp=32–46}}

The chapters 14 to 20 are dedicated to plot and structure of underlying text behind the performance art.{{Sfn|Tieken|1998|p=171}} These sections include the theory of [[Sanskrit prosody]], musical meters and the language of expression.{{Sfn| Kapila Vatsyayan | 2001}} Chapter 17 presents the attributes of poetry and figures of speech, while chapter 18 presents the art of speech and delivery in the performance arts.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn|Biswanath Bhattacharya|Ramaranjan Mukherji |1994|pp=161–163, 292–293}} The text lists ten kinds of play, presents its theory of plot, costumes, and make-up.{{Sfn|Trimbak Govind Mainkar|1978}}{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|p=8-9}} The text dedicates several chapters exclusively to women in performance arts, with chapter 24 on female theater.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|pp=104–106}} The training of actors is presented in chapters 26 and 35 of the text.{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|p=8-9}}

The theory of music, techniques for singing, and music instruments are discussed over chapters 28 to 34.{{Sfn|Tieken|1998|p=171}}{{Sfn| Kapila Vatsyayan | 2001}} The text in its final chapters describes the various types of dramatic characters, their roles and need for team work, what constitutes an ideal troupe, closing out the text with its comments of the importance of performance arts on culture.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}{{Sfn| Kapila Vatsyayan | 2001}}

==Contents==
{{Quote box | bgcolor=#FFE0BB |align=right 
|quote= '''Dramatic arts'''
<poem>
[Natyashastra praises dramatic arts] as a
comprehensive aid to the learning of virtue,
proper behavior, ethical and moral fortitude,
courage, love and adoration of the divine.
</poem>
|source =— Susan L. Schwartz<ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/>}}

The contents of the ''Natyashastra'', states Susan Schwartz, are "in part theatrical manual, part philosophy of aesthetics, part mythological history, part theology".<ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/> It is the oldest surviving encyclopedic treatise on [[dramaturgy]] from India, with sections on the theory and practice of various performance arts.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Katherine Brisbane |title=The World Encyclopedia of Contemporary Theatre: Volume 5: Asia/Pacific |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E2qKAgAAQBAJ |year=2005|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-134-92978-8 |pages=159–160|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Theo D'haen |author2=David Damrosch |author3=Djelal Kadir |title=The Routledge Companion to World Literature |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=soqoAgAAQBAJ |year=2011|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-65576-0 |pages=45 }}</ref> The text extends its reach into asking and understanding the goals of performance arts, the nature of the playwright, the artists and the spectators, their intimate relationship during the performance.<ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/>{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|p=24}} ''Natya'' topics as envisioned in this text includes what in western performing arts would include drama, dance, theatre, poetry and music.<ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/> The text integrates its aesthetics, axiology and description of arts with mythologies associated with Hindu [[Deva (Hinduism)|Deva]]s and [[Devi]]s.<ref name="GuyBeckp138"/><ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/> Performance arts, states ''Natyashastra'', are a form of Vedic ritual ceremony (yajna).<ref>ML Varadpande (1990), History of Indian Theatre, Volume 1, Abhinav, {{ISBN|978-8170172789}}, page 7</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Martin Banham |title=The Cambridge Guide to Theatre |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8qMTPAPFGXUC |year=1995|publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-43437-9 |pages=519 }}</ref>

The general approach of the text is treat entertainment as an effect, but not the primary goal of arts. The primary goal is to lift and transport the spectators, unto the expression of ultimate reality and transcendent values.<ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/><ref name=dmdp155>{{cite book|author=Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe |title=Approaches to Acting: Past and Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-KiJn_o4R5MC |year=2005|publisher= Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-4411-0381-9|pages=155–156}}</ref> The text allows, states Schwartz, the artists "enormous innovation" as they connect the playwright and the spectators, through their performance, to ''Rasa'' (the essence, juice).<ref name="Schwartz2004p12"/><ref name=dmdp102>{{cite book|author=Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe |title=Approaches to Acting: Past and Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-KiJn_o4R5MC |year=2005|publisher= Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-4411-0381-9|pages=102–104}}</ref>

The "rasa theory" of ''Natyashastra'', states Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe, presumes that bliss is intrinsic and innate in man, it exists in oneself, that manifests non-materially through spiritual and personally subjective means.<ref name=dmdp102/>{{Sfn|Sreenath Nair|2015|pp=15–38, Section 1, Chapter by Vatsyayan}} Performance arts aim to empower man to experience this ''rasa'', or re-experience it. Actors aim to journey the spectator to this aesthetic experience within him.<ref name=dmdp102/> Rasa is prepared, states ''Natya Shastra'', through a creative synthesis and expression of ''vibhava'' (determinants), ''anubhava'' (consequents) and ''vyabhicharibhava'' (transitory states).<ref name=dmdp102/>{{sfn|Radhavallabh Tripathi|1991|pp=22–28}} In the process of emotionally engaging the individual in the audience, the text outlines the use of eight sentiments – erotic, comic, pathetic, terrible, furious, odious, heroic and marvellous.<ref name=dmdp102/>{{Sfn|Ananda Lal|2004|pp=61–64}}{{Sfn|Wallace Dace|1963|pp=249–254}}

The text discusses a variety of performance arts as well as the design of the stage.{{Sfn|Natalia Lidova|2014}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Kapila Vatsyayan |title=The Square and the Circle of the Indian Arts |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vwLJc3pBzzUC |date=1997 |publisher=Abhinav Publications |isbn=978-81-7017-362-5|pages=43–46, 61–65, for various arts see 39–70}}</ref>

===Drama===
{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=240|align=left
| image1 = Anjum Bharti in Sari, for Kathak India Dance Arts.jpg | alt1=Kathak |width1=1109|height1=1600
| image2 = Flickr - dalbera - Danseuse de Kuchipudi jouant Krishna (musée Guimet).jpg | alt2= Kuchipudi |width2=1413|height2=2048
| image3 = Nirupam Rajendra.JPG | alt3= Mahamaya|width3=4000|height3=3000 
| image4 = Bharathanatyam By Ranjitha.jpg | alt4= Bharatanatyam |width4=4472 |height4= 3456
| image5 = Krishnakahi Kashyap performing Sattriya Dance.jpg | alt5= Sattriya |width5=2592|height5=3872
| image6 = Dance arts in India 2012.jpg | alt6=Janus|width6=1200 |height6=1800
| footer = Examples of classical dance arts
}}
The ''Natyashastra'' defines drama in verse 6.10 as that which aesthetically arouses joy in the spectator, through the medium of actor's art of communication, that helps connect and transport the individual into a super sensual inner state of being.{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|p=3}} The ''Natya'' connects through ''abhinaya'', that is applying body-speech-mind and scene, wherein asserts ''Natyashastra'', the actors use two practices of ''dharmi'' (performance), in four styles and four regional variations, accompanied by song and music in a playhouse carefully designed to achieve ''siddhi'' (success in production).{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|p=3}} Drama in this ancient Sanskrit text, thus is an art to engage every aspect of life, in order to glorify and gift a state of joyful consciousness.{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|p=5}}

The text discusses the universal and inner principles of drama, that it asserts successfully affects and journeys the audience to a supersensual state of discovery and understanding. The stories and plots were provided by the Itihasas (epics), the [[Puranas]] and the Kathas genre of Hindu literature.{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|p=5}}

The text states that the playwright should know the ''bhavas'' (inner state of being) of all characters in the story, and it is these bhavas that the audience of that drama connects with.{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|p=5}} The hero is shown to be similar to everyone in some ways, trying to achieve the [[Puruṣārtha|four goals]] of human life in Hindu philosophy, then the ''vastu'' (plot) emerges through the "representation of three worlds – the divine, the human, the demonic".<ref name=sallybanesp27/>{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|pp=5–19}} Drama has dharma, it has artha, it has kama, it has humor, fighting and killing. The best drama shows the good and the bad, actions and feelings, of each character, whether god or man.<ref name=sallybanesp27/>{{Sfn|Tarla Mehta|1995|pp=5–19}}

According to ''Natyashastra'', state Sally Banes and Andre Lepeck, drama is that art which accepts human beings are in different inner states when they arrive as audience, then through the art performed, it provides enjoyment to those wanting pleasure, solace to those in grief, calmness to those who are worried, energy to those who are brave, courage to those who are cowards, eroticism to those who want company, enjoyment to those who are rich, knowledge to those who are uneducated, wisdom to those who are educated.<ref name=sallybanesp27/>{{Sfn|Adya Rangacharya|1998}} Drama represents the truths about life and worlds, through emotions and circumstances, to deliver entertainment, but more importantly ethos, questions, peace and happiness.<ref name=sallybanesp27>{{cite book|author1=Sally Banes|author2=Andre Lepecki|title=The Senses in Performance|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gLPBni9awkYC |year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-46070-0|pages=27–28}}</ref>

The function of drama and the art of theatre, as envisioned in ''Natyashastra'' states Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe, is to restore the human potential, man's journey of "delight at a higher level of consciousness", and a life that is enlightened.<ref>{{cite book|author=Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe |title=Approaches to Acting: Past and Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-KiJn_o4R5MC |year=2005|publisher= Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-4411-0381-9|page=155|quote='''Quote:''' (...) "the function of the art of theatre, described in the Natyasastra is to restore full human potential, life in enlightenment. The concept of beauty in Indian tradition is, therefore, conceived and presented as the experience of delight at a higher level of consciousness."}}</ref>

The text goes into specifics to explain the means available within dramatic arts to achieve its goals. Just like the taste of food, states ''Natyashastra'', is determined by combination of vegetables, spices and other articles such as sugar and salt, the audience tastes dominant states of a drama through expression of words, gestures and temperaments.{{Sfn|Ghosh|2002|pp=105–106}} These dominant states are love, mirth, sorrow, anger, energy, terror, disgust and astonishment. Further, states the text, there are 33 psychological states which are transitory such as discouragement, weakness, apprehension, intoxication, tiredness, anxiety, agitation, despair, impatience.{{Sfn|Ghosh|2002|pp=102, note the text lists all 33}} There are eight temperamental states that a drama can deploy to carry its message.{{Sfn|Ghosh|2002|pp=102–103}} The text describes four means of communication between the actors and the audience – words, gestures, dresses and ''aharya'' (make ups, cosmetics), all of which should be harmonious with the temperament envisioned in the drama.{{Sfn|Ghosh|2002|p=103}} The text discusses the dominant, transitory and temperamental states, for dramatic arts, and the means that an artist can use to express these states, in chapters 6 through 7.{{Sfn|Ghosh|2002|pp=103–147}}

The ''Natyasastra'' describes the stage for performance arts as the sacred space for artists, and discusses the specifics of stage design, positioning the actors, the relative locations, movement on stage, entrance and exit, change in background, transition, objects displayed on the stage, and such architectural features of a theatre; the text asserts that these aspects help the audience get absorbed in the drama as well as understand the message and the meaning being communicated.<ref name=kpramodp13>{{cite book|author=Kale Pramod |title=The Theatric Universe: (a Study of the Natyasastra) |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yRdNBKIHnjkC |date=1974 |publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-118-8 |pages=13–31}}</ref><ref name="Liu2016p222">{{cite book|author=David Mason |editor=Siyuan Liu|title=Routledge Handbook of Asian Theatre |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H1iFCwAAQBAJ |year=2016|publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-317-27886-3 |pages=222–225 |display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Chris Salter |title=Entangled: Technology and the Transformation of Performance |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZBJbIP0fMr0C |date=2010 |publisher=MIT Press |isbn=978-0-262-19588-1 |pages=xxii–xxiii }}</ref> After the 10th-century, [[Hindu temple]]s were designed to include stages for performance arts (for example, ''[[Koothambalam|kuttampalams]]''), or prayer halls (for example, ''namghar'') that seconded as dramatic arts stage, based on the square principle described in the ''Natyasastra'', such as those in the peninsular and eastern states of India.<ref name="Liu2016p222"/>

===Song and dance in arts===
The ''Natyasastra'' discusses Vedic songs, and also dedicates over 130 verses to non-Vedic songs.{{Sfn|Pandurang Vaman Kane|1971|pp=45–46}} Chapter 17 of the text is entirely dedicated to poetry and the structure of a song, which it states is also the template for composing plays.<ref>{{cite book|author=Susan L. Schwartz |title=Rasa: Performing the Divine in India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-BXVSmT1WhMC |year=2004|publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=978-0-231-13144-5|pages=17–18}}</ref> Its chapter 31 asserts that there are seven types of songs, and these are ''Mandraka'', ''Aparantaka'', ''Rovindaka'', ''Prakari'', ''Ullopyaka'', ''Ovedaka'' and ''Uttara''.{{Sfn|Pandurang Vaman Kane|1971|p=46}} It also elaborates on 33 melodic [[alankara]]s in songs.{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|pp=29}} These are melodic tools of art for any song, and they are essential. Without these melodic intonations, states the text, a song becomes like "a night without the moon, a river without water, a creeper with a flower and a woman without an ornament".{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|pp=30}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Manjusree Tyagi|title=Significance of compositional forms in Hindustani classical music |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GXgHAQAAMAAJ |date=1997 |publisher=Pratibha |isbn=978-81-85268-63-7 |page=89}}</ref> A song also has four basic architectural ''varna'' to empower its meaning, and these tone patterns are ascending line, steady line, descending line and the unsteady line.{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|pp=30}}

The ideal poem produces bliss in the reader, or listener. It transports the audience into an imaginative world, transforms his inner state, and delivers him to a higher level of consciousness, suggests ''Natyashastra''.<ref name=schwartzrasa18>{{cite book|author=Susan L. Schwartz |title=Rasa: Performing the Divine in India |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-BXVSmT1WhMC |year=2004|publisher=Columbia University Press |isbn=978-0-231-13144-5|pages=18–19}}</ref> Great songs do not instruct or lecture, they delight and liberate from within to a state of godlike ecstasy.<ref name=schwartzrasa18/> According to Susan Schwartz, these sentiments and ideas of ''Natyashastra'' likely influenced the devotional songs and musical trends of the [[Bhakti movement]] that emerged in Hinduism during the second half of the 1st millennium CE.<ref name=schwartzrasa18/>

Indian dance (''nritta'', नृत्त) traditions, states Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe, have roots in the aesthetics of ''Natyashastra''.<ref name=katherineyoung20/><ref>{{cite book|author=Daniel Meyer-Dinkgräfe |title=Approaches to Acting: Past and Present |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-KiJn_o4R5MC |year=2005|publisher= Bloomsbury Academic |isbn=978-1-4411-0381-9|pages=6–7}}</ref> The text defines the basic dance unit to be a ''karana'', which is a specific combination of the hands and feet integrated with specific body posture and gait (''sthana'' and ''chari'' respectively).{{Sfn|Sunil Kothari|Avinash Pasricha|2001|pp=117–118}}{{Sfn|Nina Mirnig|Peter-Daniel Szanto|Michael Williams|2013|pp=186–187}}  Chapter 4 describes 108 ''karanas'' as the building blocks to the art of dance.{{Sfn|Sunil Kothari|Avinash Pasricha|2001|pp=117–118}}{{Sfn|Nina Mirnig|Peter-Daniel Szanto|Michael Williams|2013|pp=174–177}} The text states the various movements of major and minor limbs with facial states as means of articulating ideas and expressing emotions.{{Sfn|Sunil Kothari|Avinash Pasricha|2001|pp=117–118}}{{Sfn|Ananda Lal|2004|pp=95–99}}

===Music and musical instruments===
The ''Natyashastra'' is, states Emmie Te Nijenhuis, the oldest surviving text that systematically treats "the theory and instruments of Indian music".{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|pp=3–4}} Music has been an integral part of performance arts in the Hindu tradition since its Vedic times,<ref>{{cite book|author=Guy L. Beck |title=Sacred Sound: Experiencing Music in World Religions |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t-IeHbqAfSsC |year=2006|publisher=Wilfrid Laurier University Press|isbn=978-0-88920-421-8 |pages=114–123 }}</ref> and the theories of music found in the ''Natyasastra'' are also found in many [[Puranas]], such as the [[Markandeya Purana]].{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|pp=3–4, 7–25}}

{{multiple image|perrow = 2|total_width=240|align=right
| image1 = Veena.png | alt1=Veena |width1=600|height1=400
| image2 = Banshri.jpg | alt2= Flute |width2=165|height2=215
| image3 = Lukobadya nagara.jpg | alt3= Pushkala Nagara drums |width3=454|height3=325 
| image4 = Cymbals (PSF).png | alt4= Cymbals |width4=2046 |height4= 2491
| footer = Musical instrument types mentioned in the ''Natyashastra'' (string, flute, drums and cymbals).<ref name="BaumerBrandon1993p117"/>
}}
The ancient Indian tradition, before the ''Natyashastra'' was finalized, classified musical instruments into four groups based on their acoustic principle (how they work, rather than the material they are made of).{{Sfn|Rowell|2015|pp=13-14}} The ''Natyashastra'' accepts these four categories as given, and dedicates four separate chapters to them, one each on stringed instruments (chordophones), hollow instruments (aerophones), solid instruments (idiophones), and covered instruments (membranophones).{{Sfn|Rowell|2015|pp=13-14}}

Chapters 15 and 16 of the text discuss [[Sanskrit prosody]] in a manner similar to those found in more ancient [[Vedanga]] texts such as the ''Pingala Sutras''.{{Sfn|Nina Mirnig|Peter-Daniel Szanto|Michael Williams|2013|pp=350–351}}{{Sfn|Ghosh|2002|pp=248–292}} Chapters 28 through 34 are dedicated to music, both vocal and instrument based.{{Sfn|Maurice Winternitz|2008|p=9, 654}} Chapter 28, discusses the harmonic scale, calling the unit of tonal measurement or audible unit as ''Śruti'',{{Sfn|Emmie Te Nijenhuis|1974|p=14}} with verse 28.21 introducing the musical scale as follows,<ref>NA Jairazbhoy (1985), [http://ethnomusicologyreview.ucla.edu/sites/default/files/prevol2.pdf Harmonic Implications of Consonance and Dissonance in Ancient Indian Music], Pacific Review of Ethnomusicology, University of California Los Angeles, pages 28–31</ref>

